Disk Forensics > [T9]: Windows Timeline: Analyzing User Activities and Applications

(2) Windows Timeline

In April 2018, Microsoft released an update for Windows that introduced a new feature called "Timeline". This feature displays a list of the user's activities to make it easy for the user to access open applications he recently used. To open the Windows Timeline, you can press the "Windows key" + "Tab KEY". The Timeline data is stored in the "C:\Users<user>\AppData\Local\ConnectedDevicesPlatform\L.<user>\ActivitiesCache.db" file.

Eric Zimmerman has written a tool called "WxTCMD" that can analyze the Timeline database and parse it into a CSV file. 

 

WxTCMD output


The "ActivitiesCache.db" database contains several tables. The tool extracts the contents of each of these tables. The Activity and Activity_PackageID tables are the most important ones for us. Eric has also written another tool called "TimeLine Explorer" that can be used to view the generated CSV file in a more user-friendly way, with filtering and search capabilities.

 

Timeline Explorer

In the previous figure, you can see the most critical columns in the Activity table. This table contains information such as the executable's path, the name of the application the user sees (display text column), and the usage duration.
